p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple myeloma\u003C/strong\u003E is most commonly associated with punched-out lesions in the skull. These lesions are due to increased osteoclast activity stimulated by the cancerous plasma cells, leading to bone resorption and characteristic radiographic findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteosarcoma\u003C/strong\u003E presents with a sunburst pattern or Codman\u0027s triangle on imaging\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPaget\u0027s disease of bone\u003C/strong\u003E often shows thickened, disorganised bone rather than discrete lesions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoporosis\u003C/strong\u003E  is characterised by generalised bone thinning, not focal lesions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects joints and may cause erosions, but not punched-out skull lesions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Punched-out lesions in the skull are characteristic of multiple myeloma.","Multiple myeloma is a cancer of plasma cells that often leads to bone lesions due to increased osteoclast activity.","Radiographic imaging can reveal these distinctive bone lesions, aiding in the diagnosis of multiple myeloma."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Mohan, H. (2018). Textbook of pathology. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers","Momodu II, Savaliya V. Osteomyelitis. [Updated 2023 May 31]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK532250/","Folpe, A., \u0026 Nielsen, G. P. (Eds.). (2022). Bone and Soft Tissue Pathology E-Book: A Volume in the Foundations in Diagnostic Pathology Series. Elsevie